@node NUTZUNG "Nutzung"

    ***********************************************************************

    ! ATTENTION !

    The save working range of this program is:


      100 Milli-Ohm up to 990 Mega-Ohm.

    Value outside of this range will be answered by an  error  notification
    or a false value at the integer gadget.

    That range will include all normal used colorcoded  resistor.  (Try  to
    buy an resistor of 55 milli-Ohm or 999 mega-Ohm with color-rings ... :-)


    ************************************************************************

    Some preliminary remarks:

    The colorring-coded resistor have ALWAYS ONLY 2 digits for the value.

    for example:

    220 Ohm, 33 Kilo-Ohm, 2200 Milli-Ohm

    NEVER 125 Ohm or 22,3 Kilo-Ohm or 2230 Milli-Ohm

    If you give such a 3 digit value the programm will ignore the value  of
    the third digit, but it will accept the third digit.

    for example:

    125 Ohm the programm reads as 120 Ohm
    22,3 Kilo-Ohm the programm reads as 22 Kilo-Ohm

    4,7 Kilo-Ohm the programm will accept, but it MUST be  insert  as  4700
    Ohm. The reason is: the gadget you will give in the value is an integer
    gadget. It can't work with floating point numbers.

    The same you have to take into account with 1 digit numbers, like
    1 Kilo-Ohm.

    Give in 1000 Ohms instead.

    In the range of Milli-Ohm you can't  give  in  values  lower  than  100
    Milli-Ohms because there is no way to colorcode such a value.



    Now ... the program itself:

    The Interface is near selfexplain.

    The color-gadgets at the left you must klick in the order of the  rings
    at the resistor.

    for example: brown - black - yellow

    (The first ring is never black - equal 0. By this  reason  the  program
    will not react if you click at first at the "black" button.)

    The colors will appear in the symbolic resistor at  the  right  in  the
    order you have clicked.

    In the middle in the integer gadget you immediately will see the  value
    the color represents.

    You also con give in the value of the resistor:

    1. Choose the range (Ohm ... Kilo-Ohm ...)

    2. Give in your value in the Integer-Gadget.

    (Integer numbers are not bigger then 10 digits.  So  the  Gadget  won't
    accept bigger numbers.)

    Immediately you can see the colors of  the  rings  that  represet  your
    value.

    Like I've written above ... big values will be transcalculated.

    Please remember: NEVER floating point numbers like 4,7 ...

    If the value in the integer gadget is bigger  than  9999,  the  program
    will  calculate  it  to  the next biggest range, where the value can be
    displayed as integer numbers.

    for example:

    Your input is in the range of Ohm: 24000

    After ENTER the  the  displayed  value  will  automatic  switch  to  24
    Kilo-Ohm.

    Not so if your input is at Ohm: 2400

    The gadget can't show 2,4 Kilo-Ohm. (See above ...)

    another example:

    Input at Milli-Ohm : 240000000

    After ENTER you will see : 240 Kilo-Ohm

    The 4.ring will show you the tolerance value of the resistor. Most this
    ring  ist  in  a  bigger  distance like the other rings. If there is no
    4.ring the tolerance is 20%.

    Also at this place you have two ways:

    1. Klick at the color and you will  see  the  tolerance  value  in  the
       cycle-gadget.

    2. Choose the tolerance value with the cycle-gadget and  you  will  see
       the correspondending color.

    The only way, if you are not sure if you have read the colors  correct,
    to  get the value of the resistor: use a resistor measuring instrument.

    I'll not held liable, if there is any damage by using this program  ...
    you are warned ... ;-)

    Before you work with a new resistor,  please  click  "new"  or  'n'  or
    right-AMIGA&n.

    There is also a litte menu. I think I havn't to explain it ...


    Quit or 'q' or right-AMIGA&q or ESC .... na, what ....

    Now, I think, all is explained .... :-)


@endnode
@node INSTALLATION "Installation"

    Nothing easier than that ....

    Copy the whole directory at a place, you  want  put  it  in.  Copy  the
    classes-directory  to  SYS:classes  or  the  textfield.gadget  in it to
    SYS:Classes/gadgets.

    Starting the program is possible by Icon (Workbench) or CLI.

    Before starting by CLI set the stack to 50000.
    (Input in CLI : stack 50000)

    By the other way the stack will overflow by  ending  the  program.  And
    your AMIGA will be send to NIRWANA ....

    That's all .... :-)

@endnode
